+#### `contents.watchFocusedEditableText([options, ]callback)` _Experimental_
+
+* `options` [FocusedEditableTextWatchOptions](structures/focused-editable-text-watch-options.md) (optional)
+* `callback` Function
+  * `info` [FocusedEditableText | null](structures/focused-editable-text.md) -
+    The current focused editable text snapshot, or `null` if no focused
+    editable text can be read.
+
+Returns [`FocusedEditableTextWatcher`](structures/focused-editable-text-watcher.md) -
+a watcher that can be closed to stop receiving callbacks.
+
+Starts watching the focused editable text state in this WebContents. The
+callback is called asynchronously once with the current snapshot after the
+watcher is created, and then again when Electron observes input state, caret,
+selection, composition, or focus changes that may affect the focused editable
+text snapshot.
+
+Each watcher owns its own `options`, so multiple callers can watch the same
+WebContents with different `mode`, `maxLength`, or `throttleMs` values without
+overwriting each other. Call
+[`watcher.close()`](structures/focused-editable-text-watcher.md) to stop a
+specific watcher. The watcher remains active even if the returned object is not
+retained by JavaScript, but keeping the returned object is the only way to close
+that watcher before the WebContents is destroyed.
+
+The watcher coalesces changes while an asynchronous snapshot is in flight and
+uses `throttleMs` to limit callback frequency. It reports the latest snapshot
+after coalescing rather than queueing every intermediate input state.
+
+Password inputs report `null`. Custom editors backed by DOM-editable content
+are handled on a best-effort basis. The watcher is not a general DOM mutation
+observer; editors backed by canvas, virtual documents, or application-internal
+models may only expose the focused DOM control.
+
 #### `contents.isLoading()`
 
 Returns `boolean` - Whether web page is still loading resources.
